<promed@promedmail.org>

[This supersedes http://apps.who.int/gho/data/view.ebola-sitrep.ebola-summary-latest?lang=en of 23 Dec 2014, which has a table showing 19 340 cases, 7518 deaths.

The difference between the totals in the 1st paragraph of the summary above and the 1st paragraph of "Countries with widespread and intense transmission" may be explained by the inclusion of only the 3 countries most concerned in the table. 16 pages of detailed tables, maps and graphs are included, but it should be noted that WHO has acknowledged that all data from the 3 countries are incomplete, and only an unknown portion of these figures are confirmed, so they cannot be used to make reliable calculations of case fatality rates or detailed trends. - Mod.JW]

******
[2] Sierra Leone: case count decreasing
Date: Mon 22 Dec 2014
Source: AllAfrica, Premium Times report [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201412230143.html


Ebola slows in Sierra Leone as community records zero infection for weeks
-------------------------------------------------------------------
The discharge of the last Ebola patient from Sierra Leone's Kailahun district, announced by the district medical officer of Kailahun, James Squire, has further heightened hopes that the increase in incidence of the disease in the country is slowing down. "... the Kailahun district has recorded zero infection for several weeks," Mr Squire declared. Sierra Leone has recorded the highest number of Ebola cases of the 3 most-affected countries that also included Liberia and Guinea.

The latest case numbers (deaths) reported by WHO aer as follows: Sierra Leone 8356 cases (2085 deaths), Liberia 7797 (3290) and Guinea 2416 (1525), with a total of 6915 lives lost in the 3 countries as well as in Mali, Nigeria and the USA...

