[3] Sierra Leone: 1st conviction under Ebola laws
Date: Wed 24 Dec 2014
Source: Daily Mail, AFP (Agence France-Presse) report [edited]
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-2885838/First-conviction-Sierra-Leone-Ebola-laws.html


1st conviction under Ebola laws
-------------------------------
A village chief has become the 1st person in Sierra Leone to be jailed under laws aimed at preventing the spread of the Ebola virus, court officials and lawyers said. Amadu Kargbo was sentenced to 6 months in jail by a court in the south western city of Moyamba for secretly burying the dead and failing to report a sick patient, court official Foday Fofanah told AFP. He was also fined one million leones (USD 235) and ordered to spend 21 days in quarantine before going to jail.

Lawyers in the capital Freetown said it was the 1st known conviction under the country's Ebola laws. Fofanah said the chief had pleaded guilty to secretly burying his daughter, who had died of Ebola. He added that Kargbo's wife had also died after attending the funeral of another family member, although it was not clear if any of the charges related to his wife's death and burial...

Authorities have banned public gatherings as well as New Year celebrations as part of sweeping efforts to stem the spread of the virus...

