USA: airport screening for Ebola amid holiday rush
--------------------------------------------------
Date: Tue 23 Dec 2014
Source: The Daily Signal [edited]
http://dailysignal.com/2014/12/23/amid-holiday-travel-rush-officials-keep-eye-1700-ebola/


The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [US CDC] continues to screen passengers flying into the US for Ebola, even amid the Holiday rush. Travelers entering the US from the 4 West African countries affected by Ebola: Guinea, Sierra Leone, Liberia and Mali, continue to [be routed] through 5 airports: Washington Dulles International [Virginia], Chicago O'Hare [Illinois], John F Kennedy in New York, Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta [Georgia], and Newark Liberty [New Jersey].

Officials with Customs and Border Protection 1st isolate travelers coming from these countries and conduct a screening that includes a questionnaire and contact form. Individuals also have their temperatures taken. Eight passengers were taken to medical facilities for additional screening, according to data compiled by the Department of Homeland Security. In most cases where symptoms of Ebola are present, Nordlund said, patients may test positive for the flu or malaria instead. Once individuals leave the airport, it becomes the responsibility of state and local officials at their destination to continue to monitor them.

Local and state health officials actively monitor about 1700 persons for symptoms of Ebola, although the number fluctuates daily as travelers move in and out of the 21-day monitoring window. The total number being monitored is not published on [CDC's] website, Kristen Nordlund, a spokeswoman for the CDC in Atlanta, said. Some have presented symptoms such as fever, but none has tested positive for Ebola.

Even though media coverage of the Ebola outbreak has quieted down, as Sharyl Attkisson, senior independent contributor to The Daily Signal, noted in an interview Sunday, infectious disease experts still worry about Ebola and the possibility of it spreading to the United States.

[byline: Melissa Quinn]

